    "id": "312fe8dd-acd6-81be-a056-fd1a35296cea",
    "markdown": "JavaScript has two operators for providing fallback values: `||` (logical OR) and `??` (nullish coalescing). They look similar but behave very differently.\n## The Difference\n`||` returns the right-hand side for any **falsy** value:\n```javascript\n0 || \"default\"        // \"default\"\n\"\" || \"default\"       // \"default\"\nfalse || \"default\"    // \"default\"\nnull || \"default\"     // \"default\"\nundefined || \"default\" // \"default\"\n```\n`??` returns the right-hand side only for `null` or `undefined`:\n```javascript\n0 ?? \"default\"        // 0\n\"\" ?? \"default\"       // \"\"\nfalse ?? \"default\"    // false\nnull ?? \"default\"     // \"default\"\nundefined ?? \"default\" // \"default\"\n```\n## When It Matters\nThis distinction is critical when `0`, `\"\"`, or `false` are valid values:\n```javascript\n// Bug: user set port to 0, but we override it\nconst port = userConfig.port || 3000; // 3000\n\n// Correct: only fallback if not provided\nconst port = userConfig.port ?? 3000; // 0\n```\n```javascript\n// Bug: user explicitly set name to \"\"\nconst name = input.name || \"Anonymous\"; // \"Anonymous\"\n\n// Correct: respect the empty string\nconst name = input.name ?? \"Anonymous\"; // \"\"\n```\n## Rule of Thumb\n- Use `??` when you want to handle **missing values** (null/undefined)\n- Use `||` when you want to handle **any falsy value**\nIn practice, `??` is almost always what you want when providing defaults.",
